§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We consider knapsack problems in which there is more than
    one knapsack. ⦉
⦉

§ Definition ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Given $p: \set{1, …, n} → 𝗥$, $w: \set{1, …, n} → 𝗥$ and
    $c ∈ 𝗥_+^n$, find $x: \set{0,…,m} × \set{0, …, n} →
    \{0,1\}$ to
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ \begin{aligned} ⦉

      ‖ \text{maximize} & \quad \textstyle ∑_{i = 1}^m ∑_{j =
        1}^{n} p_j x_{ij} ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ \text{subject to} & \quad \textstyle ∑_{j = 1}^n
        w_jx_{ij} ≤ c_i , \quad i = 1, …, n᜶ ⦉

      ‖ & \quad \textstyle ∑_{j = 1}^{n} x_{ij} ≤ 1, \quad i =
        1, …, n ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ & \quad x_{ij} ∈ \{0,1\} \quad i = 1, …, m, j = 1,
        …, n ⦉

      ‖ \end{aligned} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Here $x_{ij}$ is one if and only if item $j$ is assigned
    to knapsack $i$. ⦉

  ‖ The above is called the ❬multiple knapsack problem❭ (or ❬0-1
    muliple knapsack problem❭). ⦉
⦉

